  
  In order to commit, thresh num stores across all objects must respond with Prepared(VoteCommit)
  Actual Tx is done only on primary object so we'll receive only a subset of Accept messages
  What we're really looking for is the Delayed Prepared(VoteCommit) messages, not delayed accept
  Per-store tx resolution will ensure they eventually discover the right version of the object.
  Need a bit more though..., VoteAbort doesn't mean the update was missed.
  
  Could add another message that is unconditionally broadcast "Committed" across all stores.
  Missed update finalization delay takes this into account
     - This would also allow the finalization delay to be tailored for each transaction, which
       could be handy.
  
  
  * Update Config File to use allocaters for pool error handler
  
  * Update TansactionManager to call checkMissedUpdates() on Tx drivers on a periodic basis.
    Driver forwards this call to Finalizers?
    could also add an optional missedUpdateDelay: Option[Duration] to each finalizer
    Tx then takes the max delay and calls setFinalStores(set) with the result
       -> This looks like a good approach
     
  * Add automatic FA addition

  * Switch per-store-set config to take Tree args
     - list of object allocater UUIDs
     - list of tier node sizes

  * object allocaters
  * Object Update Error recovery/logging
  * Failed store rebuild
  
  Missed Updates.
      - Multiple Potential Strategies
      - Configured on a per-pool basis
      
      * create PerStoreMissedUpdate
          - has log miss method which is used by the FinalizationAction
          - per-store key in Pool object is PerStoreMissedUpdateUUID + indexByte
          
        * on restore
          - delete tx uses a revision lock on the being-restored object AND requirement that the key-value timestamp is
            exactly equal to the expected value. Subsequent insertion will update to a new timestamp.
          
      
      Per-store UUID Set:
          - KeyValueList per store
          - Used as a set of object UUIDs
          - On missed update, blind insert into the list
          - Multiple inserts for same object will simply get compacted
          - Can point at alternate pool with custom IDA and use-case-optimized backing stores
          - Impl as a standard MissedUpdateFinalizationAction
              - Allows easy swap
              - Semantics already match exactly
              - Fully independent of per-pool failure marking approach/impl
              - FA can lookup the Pool for each object
                   - Then loads the FailedUpdateMarker for each pool,object
                   - FA completes when each marker completes
                       - Separate "micro-process" for each object
                       - Separate Transactions (no need for additional contention) with retry mechanisms
              - Two types of UpdateMarkers
                   - SingleStoreMarker - updates on a per-store basis
                   - MultiStoreMarker  - updates all missed stores for an object simultaneously 
              - Place on Transaction interface? e.g: protected [aspen] disableFailedUpdateTracking() ?
                   - Only MissedUpdateFinalizationAction calls the disable
                   - MUFA process: 
                       system.transactUntilSuccessful { tx =>
                         tx.disableFailedUpdateTracking
                         missedUpdateMarker.mark(obj)
                       }
                      
                       
          - We don't need recursive updates to these trees. They're used in a scanning-like manner anyway.
              - Compactions will overwrite nodes anyway
              - Could easily create daemon scanning agents
      

Basic Error Handling
  * Read
      - SuperSimpleRetryingReadDriver
          Fixed delay between retries
          
  * Transaction
      - SimpleClientTransactionDriver
          Retransmits prepare with fixed delay. Update data stops being sent after first response is received
      - SimpleStorageNodeTxMgr
          Background Task polls transactions. If last heartbeat exceeds a threshold timeout, launch a Tx driver
      - SimpleFixedDelayTransactionDriver
          Starts a new Paxos round after a fixed delay. Should be sufficient for simple situations
          
  * Allocation Recovery
      - SuperSimpleRetryingAllocationDriver
          Fixed delay between retransmit
      - SimpleStorageNodeAllocationManager
          Polls in-progress allocations. If a threshold is exceeded, launch the recovery process
      - SimpleAllocationRecoveryProcess
          Queries Tx status and awaits completion
          If version of allocating object hasnt changed, bump the version
          Once the version is known to have changed, look up the object in the allocation tree.
          If present, the object was successfully allocated. Otherwise the object may be discarded
           
  


